/*
https://leetcode.com/problems/merge-k-sorted-lists/description/?envType=company&envId=nvidia&favoriteSlug=nvidia-all

You are given an array of k linked-lists lists, each linked-list is sorted in ascending order.

Merge all the linked-lists into one sorted linked-list and return it.

 

Example 1:

Input: lists = [[1,4,5],[1,3,4],[2,6]]
Output: [1,1,2,3,4,4,5,6]
Explanation: The linked-lists are:
[
  1->4->5,
  1->3->4,
  2->6
]
merging them into one sorted linked list:
1->1->2->3->4->4->5->6
Example 2:

Input: lists = []
Output: []
Example 3:

Input: lists = [[]]
Output: []
 

Constraints:

k == lists.length
0 <= k <= 104
0 <= lists[i].length <= 500
-104 <= lists[i][j] <= 104
lists[i] is sorted in ascending order.
The sum of lists[i].length will not exceed 104.

*/

/*
Since each linked list is already sorted, the minimum element among all remaining nodes must be present at the head of one of the lists.
I use a min heap to keep track of the smallest current head among all lists.
Initially, I add the head of every non-empty list to the heap. Then I repeatedly remove the smallest node, attach it to the result list, and if that node has a next node, I push the next node into the heap.
This way, the heap never stores more than k nodes, and each node is processed exactly once.
Time: O(N log k)
Space: O(k)
space complexity is O(k) because we are not creating a new result list.
We are reusing the same existing ListNode objects.
*/

public static ListNode mergeKLists(ListNode[] lists) {
    if (lists == null || lists.length == 0) {
        return null;
    }

    PriorityQueue<ListNode> pq = new PriorityQueue<>(
        (a, b) -> Integer.compare(a.val, b.val)
    );

    // Add the head of each non-empty list
    for (ListNode node : lists) {
        if (node != null) {
            pq.offer(node);
        }
    }

    ListNode dummyNode = new ListNode(-1);
    ListNode current = dummyNode;

    while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
        // Get the smallest current node
        ListNode node = pq.poll();

        // Add the next node from the same list
        if (node.next != null) {
            pq.offer(node.next);
        }

        // Attach the smallest node to result
        current.next = node;
        current = current.next;
    }

    return dummyNode.next;
}
